                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d40">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/3811: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-28T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >March 28, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 28—10:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>539. Under date March 24, Embassy telegraphed Drumright at Sian (1) to keep us
                    currently advised all pertinent information he could obtain (our 485, March 18
                    and last paragraph 497, March 21;<note n="14" xml:id="d40fn14">Neither
                        printed.</note> (2) to keep in touch with Americans in areas which might be
                    threatened with view to advising them, if circumstances should warrant, to
                    withdraw in ample time to safer places. He replied under date March 25 he was
                    advising American missionaries Chengchow area, also Hsuchang and Chowkiakow,
                    Honan, to withdraw and stated he felt all Americans should be formally advised
                    to retire from Anhwei and Honan Provinces. Embassy telegraphed approval March 26
                    and is so informing mission offices here requesting that they notify their
                    missionaries to leave those areas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
